You can use the `as` keyword in TypeScript to assert a specific type for a value, even if the type system thinks it might be something else.

For example, if you have a variable `x` that is of type `string`, but you know that it will always contain a valid email address, you can assert its type to be `email`, like this:
```
const x: string = 'example@example.com';
const y = x as email;
```
This tells the type system that you know `x` is actually of type `email`, even though it is typed as `string`.

You can also use this technique to assert the type of a value that is returned from a function, or that is part of an interface.
```
function foo(): string | email {
  return 'example@example.com';
}

const x = foo();
const y = x as email;
```
Or
```
interface MyInterface {
  value: string;
}

const x: MyInterface = { value: 'example@example.com' };
const y = x as { value: email };
```

